h-century Edinburgh owed much to the men who worked in the Court of Session as members of the unique institution known as the College of Justice. James Boswell, Lord Kames, Henry Dundas and Walter Scott are just some of those who emerged from the College to influence Scotland’s place in Europe.Key FeaturesAn original and wide-ranging study based on primary sources, including newly discovered records from the Court of SessionGives you insights into the history of urban administration, the legal profession and the Court of SessionConsiders the legal and social community responsible for the development of Scots law at a key period in its developmentFor anyone studying the sources and singularity of Scots Law, and the social history of the 18th century"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCivil procedurexHistoryxScotland. 0aCivil procedurezScotlandxHistory. 0aJustice, Administration ofxHistoryxScotland. 0aJustice, Administration ofzScotlandxHistory. 4aLaw. 7aLAW / Courts.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074864577040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780748645787?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748645787423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748645787/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK